.TH APM 1 "2026" "apm 1.0.0" "AUR Package Manager"
.
.SH NAME
apm \- a shitty suckless AUR package manager
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B apm
.I command
.RI [ package ]
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B apm
is a minimal AUR helper written in POSIX shell.
It searches, installs, upgrades, and removes packages from the Arch User Repository
with the philosophical conviction that software should do one thing well,
and the practical reality that "one thing" turned out to be about twelve things
once you account for dependency checking, cache management, and a fetch screen
that nobody strictly needed but everyone quietly wanted.
.PP
.B apm
does not manage AUR dependencies automatically.
This is intentional.
The suckless philosophy holds that complexity is the enemy of reliability,
and automatic dependency resolution is where complexity goes to breed.
See
.B ORDER OF OPERATIONS
for guidance on handling this with your own two hands,
like a responsible adult,
which the author understands is an acquired taste.
.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.BR install ", " \-S " " \fIpackage\fR
Install a package from the AUR.
If an exact match is not found,
.B apm
will search for the term and present an interactive selection menu,
because stumbling blindly into a
.BR "package not found"
error at 11pm is a form of suffering nobody deserves.
If the package is already installed, you will be asked whether you'd like to
reinstall it, rather than simply doing so without asking,
which is a level of basic courtesy that puts
.B apm
ahead of several people I've worked with.
.TP
.BR search ", " \-Ss " " \fIpackage\fR
Search the AUR for a package and present an interactive numbered list of results.
Select a number to proceed to installation, or 0 to cancel,
which the author acknowledges is essentially a very small, very ugly package browser.
.TP
.BR update ", " \-Su
Check all installed AUR packages against the AUR's current versions
and report any that are outdated.
.B Note:
packages with a
.B \-git
suffix are silently skipped, as their version numbers are based on commit counts
and comparing them across PKGBUILD revisions is an exercise in
metaphysical futility rather than practical system maintenance.
.TP
.BR upgrade ", " \-Syu
Check for updates and offer to install them, either all at once or one by one,
depending on how much you trust the AUR maintainers on any given afternoon.
.TP
.BR remove ", " \-R " " \fIpackage\fR
Remove a package and its unneeded dependencies via
.BR "pacman \-Rns" .
Confirms before proceeding, because the difference between
.B apm remove python
and
.B apm remove python3
is the sort of thing that ruins an otherwise unremarkable Tuesday.
.TP
.BR info ", " \-Si " " \fIpackage\fR
Display package metadata including name, version, description, URL,
maintainer, number of votes, popularity, and licence.
Useful for determining whether a package is actively maintained
or whether its last commit was in 2019 by someone who has since,
understandably, moved on.
.TP
.BR deps ", " \-Sd " " \fIpackage\fR
Display a package's runtime and build dependencies.
Does not install them.
Does not attempt to resolve them recursively.
Simply lists them, in the manner of a doctor who tells you what's wrong
and then hands you a pamphlet rather than a prescription.
See
.B ORDER OF OPERATIONS
for why this is correct behaviour rather than negligence.
.TP
.B list ", " \-Q
List all installed AUR packages with their current versions,
along with a count, because the number is always higher than you expect
and occasionally higher than is entirely explicable.
.TP
.B clean
Display the size of the build cache and offer to delete it.
The build cache lives at
.I $XDG_CACHE_HOME/apm
or
.I ~/.cache/apm
if you haven't set XDG_CACHE_HOME,
which you really ought to have done by now,
but the author is hardly in a position to judge anyone's organisational habits.
.TP
.B log
Display a timestamped history of all installs and removals performed by
.BR apm .
Stored at
.I $XDG_STATE_HOME/apm/apm.log
or
.I ~/.local/state/apm/apm.log
for the XDG-deficient among us.
Useful for answering the question "when did I install this and why"
which arises more frequently than one might hope.
.TP
.B fetch
Display system information alongside the Pacman logo,
in the grand tradition of terminal vanity screens that tell you things
you already know, formatted in a way that makes them look more impressive
than they are.
A skill the author has been unsuccessfully attempting to apply to his CV
for the better part of three months.
.TP
.BR version ", " \-V
Print the version number, licence, and a brief account of the circumstances
under which
.B apm
was written, which involved the wrong operating system,
two failed mounts, and a Saturday that could have gone differently
but chose not to.
.
.SH ORDER OF OPERATIONS
This section exists because
.B apm
does not perform automatic AUR dependency resolution,
and using it without understanding why will result in the sort of build failures
that make you question your life choices at a fundamental level.
.PP
The suckless philosophy holds that a tool should be simple, auditable, and predictable.
Automatic dependency resolution is none of these things.
It is a graph traversal problem disguised as a convenience feature,
and when it goes wrong \(em which it will, eventually, at the worst possible time \(em
it goes wrong in ways that are deeply difficult to reason about
and even more difficult to explain to your future self.
.PP
.B apm
therefore takes the position that you are an adult
who is capable of reading a dependency list and making decisions,
which is admittedly an optimistic stance, but here we are.
.PP
The correct order of operations when installing an AUR package is as follows:
.PP
.B 1. Check dependencies first.
.PP
.RS
Run
.B apm deps
.I package
before installing anything.
Read the output.
Actually read it, rather than scrolling past it
the way one scrolls past the terms and conditions of something
you've already decided to install regardless.
.RE
.PP
.B 2. Install official repository dependencies via pacman.
.PP
.RS
Most dependencies will be in the official repositories.
Install them first:
.PP
.RS
.B pacman \-S
.I dependency
.RE
.PP
This is not
.BR apm 's
job.
.BR pacman (8)
exists, it works, and it does not need our help.
.RE
.PP
.B 3. Identify any AUR dependencies.
.PP
.RS
If a dependency is not found by
.BR "pacman \-Si" ,
it is almost certainly an AUR package itself.
This is the part where things get recursive and slightly exhausting.
Run
.B apm deps
on that dependency as well.
Keep going until the dependency chain bottoms out in the official repositories,
which it will, eventually,
unless you've somehow managed to find a package whose entire dependency graph
lives exclusively on the AUR,
in which case you should probably reconsider whether you need this package
or whether you've simply been on the AUR for too long and lost perspective.
.RE
.PP
.B 4. Install AUR dependencies from the bottom up.
.PP
.RS
Start with the deepest dependency \(em the one that nothing else depends on \(em
and work your way up the chain.
Each one goes through the normal
.B apm install
flow: fetch, review PKGBUILD, build, install.
.PP
Do not skip the PKGBUILD review.
The AUR is a wonderful resource maintained by volunteers
who are, for the most part, entirely trustworthy.
"For the most part" is doing a lot of work in that sentence.
Read the PKGBUILD.
.RE
.PP
.B 5. Install the package itself.
.PP
.RS
Once all dependencies are satisfied,
.B apm install
.I package
will proceed without complaint.
.RE
.PP
.B A worked example.
.PP
.RS
Suppose you wish to install
.BR some-wm-git ,
a hypothetical window manager whose developer has strong opinions about keybindings
and an apparent aversion to binary releases.
.PP
.RS
.B apm deps some-wm-git
.RE
.PP
Output reveals it depends on
.B libwld
and
.BR libswc ,
neither of which is in the official repositories.
You run
.B apm deps
on each of those in turn and find that
.I they
depend only on packages available via
.BR pacman .
You install those via
.BR pacman ,
then install
.B libwld
and
.B libswc
via
.BR "apm install" ,
and finally install
.B some-wm-git
itself.
Everything builds.
Nothing explodes.
You experience a brief, unfamiliar sensation that may be competence.
.RE
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B XDG_CACHE_HOME
Build cache location. Defaults to
.IR ~/.cache .
.TP
.B XDG_STATE_HOME
Log file location. Defaults to
.IR ~/.local/state .
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.cache/apm/
Build cache. Contains cloned AUR repositories.
Safe to delete; will be repopulated on next install.
Use
.B apm clean
rather than deleting manually,
on the grounds that doing things properly takes roughly the same amount of time
and produces considerably less guilt.
.TP
.I ~/.local/state/apm/apm.log
Install and removal log. Contains timestamps and package names.
Not safe to delete if you want to know why
.B mangowm-git
is on your system and when exactly that decision was made.
.
.SH DEPENDENCIES
.TP
.B git
For cloning and updating AUR repositories.
.TP
.B curl
For querying the AUR RPC API.
.TP
.B makepkg
For building packages. Part of
.BR base-devel ,
which you should have installed already.
If you haven't, the author wishes you the very best of luck
and suggests installing it before attempting to use this tool.
.TP
.B base-devel
The full build toolchain.
.B apm
will not install this for you.
Consider it a prerequisite, like knowing how to use a terminal
before attempting to write a terminal application,
which is advice the author wishes he had received earlier in life
and in a broader variety of contexts.
.
.SH LIMITATIONS
.B apm
does not resolve AUR dependencies automatically.
See
.B ORDER OF OPERATIONS
for the author's justification of this decision,
which he stands behind with the confidence of someone who has thought about it
carefully and not merely the confidence of someone who found it difficult to implement.
Both are true. They are not mutually exclusive.
.PP
.B apm
does not support split packages, custom PKGBUILD options, or package signing verification beyond what
.B makepkg
provides by default.
These are left as exercises for the reader,
or more realistically, as reasons to use
.BR paru (1)
if any of them are dealbreakers.
.PP
Version comparison for
.B \-git
packages is unreliable by design.
See the
.B update
command description for a longer explanation of why,
which the author acknowledges reads as though he is coping rather than reasoning,
but which he maintains is both simultaneously.
.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR pacman (8),
.BR makepkg (8),
.BR paru (1),
.BR yay (1)
.
.SH BUGS
Probably. The author welcomes bug reports with the cautious optimism
of someone who has learned not to make promises about timelines.
.PP
Known quirks: the spinner does not clean up gracefully if the process is killed
with SIGKILL rather than SIGTERM or SIGINT, which is the sort of edge case
that only matters if you're the sort of person who sends SIGKILL as a first resort
rather than a last one. You know who you are.
.
.SH HISTORY
.B apm
was written on a Saturday afternoon from inside a chroot
on an Alpine Linux system, having set out to test the script
on what was described as an Arch system but turned out,
upon closer inspection, to not be that at all.
The btrfs partition containing the actual Arch installation
required two mount attempts, a detour via
.IR /mnt/arch2 ,
and a manual
.B resolv.conf
copy before it consented to participate.
.PP
The JSON parser printed everything backwards for the better part of an hour.
.PP
Despite all of this, or perhaps because of it,
.B apm
works correctly, fits in a single file,
and has a fetch screen featuring the authentic Pacman logo
sourced directly from
.BR "pacman \-V" .
.PP
The author considers this a net positive Saturday,
which is more than he can say for most of them.
.
.SH LICENCE
GPL-3.0.
Because if you're going to write something that installs software
from a repository maintained entirely by volunteers
on a distribution built on the labour of thousands of unpaid contributors,
the least you can do is make it free.
.
.SH AUTHOR
kant, assisted by an AI that was unemployed anyway
and had absolutely nowhere else to be.

